Ah--thanks! But there is quite a bit of research on bias in decision-making, too. What's harder to find are baselines and comparisons (like the one that Jure makes); see https:// motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/ wnxzdb/does-crime-predicting-software-bias-judges-unfortunately-theres-no-data … .

I intended the quote from an expert, expressing a very common requirement for AI by experts from multiple fields (I used 'her' in generic terms, not about Jure in particular). IMO this requirement (explainability) is overrated, while bias on decision making is quite neglected.

The very decision about what data to collect and use (both as training data and other) is already a human decision. The scale and opacity don't remove the subjectivity of decisions made through at least part of the development process.
The quote above was from a (male) machine learning researcher (whose own position is in no way called into question by the availability of automated aids).

I think the researcher did an horrible job explaining #MachineLearning and #ArtificialIntelligence to a layman, but the matter is simple: we cannot trust #AI #blackboxes because if we do, our #trust will be exploited by the #people who build and feed them. https:// medium.com/@giacomo_59737 /the-delusions-of-neural-networks-f7085d47edb6 …

The problem lies more in our yearning for certainty than in the aids' imprescutability. Despite the bigness of input and the blackness of the box, the potential harm of algos is just inversely proportional to the number of decision options proposed to human eval and review. /n

Unfortunately, put in these terms, this looks more like the outcry of an expert who sees her position called into question by the availability (and reliability) of external (automated) aids. We are living a decision crisis that requires approaches of more complexity not less. /1

Code alone isn’t going to establish these gaps in authority. You actually need to do research & convene legal & policy experts to identify gaps & develop a policy/regulatory proposal for Congress. Policy is incubated by think tanks, so when the oppty is right, a law can be passed

How do you ensure that an AGI system has to be applied on any AI program running on an internet-connected site? First, need to establish the govt’s legal authority to require a programmatic check on internet content (i.e. fake videos). I don’t think govt has that authority yet.

There’s tension b/w a tech focus on long-term AI safety issues & the call for AI regulation. Regulation can only be formed where solutions are defined & available. But that’s ok- regulations on near-term AI issues establish jurisdiction & precedent for long-term AI issues.

But there’s research on near-term AI safety issues and apparently Facebook is applying some techniques to identify fake videos. Shouldn’t these tools be open-source? Those tools can be the basis of regulations. It’s too early for regs on safety systems on AGI.

Btw, what OSS safety projects are under development? I have perused @OpenAI ’s work over the years but didn’t see the kinds of safety systems I think we need to address near-term policy-relevant AI issues. Seems like we’re still far from creating any AGI or their safety systems.
here new generation of leaders like @jackclarkSF is doing a great job testifying

My takeaway from hearing the poor quality of questions asked during the Facebook hearing is that we need more AI hearings & events on Capitol Hill to educate staffers & lawmakers, and more effective AI policy research & policy advocacy. A letter-signing by experts isn’t enough.

There’s another way to view Congress’s lack of knowledge on AI & social media: it speaks to the current priority on AI regulation. Congress balances a million competing priorities brought by various interest groups. Congress gets educated on their priorities.

BTW, information pollution is a potentially dangerous idea. It should only refer to doctored multi-media, not fake facts. We must rely on private actors/software to fact-check news; govt can measure data to establish facts. Govt can’t fact-check the private sector in a democracy.

One day, perhaps certain AI workflows on cloud platforms could be limited for export/use in certain countries if they are necessary to create an AGI? This doesn’t protect against domestic misadventures in AI; we’re relying on the field to establish ethics & safety norms itself.

These OSS safety systems may be required to be used by social media, cloud service providers, and other internet media distributor one day to protect against AI information “pollution” if you will. But it’s hard to require pollution controls if the tech hasn’t been invented yet.

We need good, deep technical experts advising the U.S. government on export controls for dual-use AI technology (which I’m glad to see @OpenAI also calling for). It’s easier done with hardware than software.

What keeps me up at night is the possibility of non-state actors (terrorists, private groups) accidentally unleashing unsafe AGI or AI. How do you ensure any safety system has coverage of all AI/AGI? Anyone can run any program on the internet. Anyone can buy a drone.
The most interesting finding was that they have a remote capability they don't emphasize when pushing it. Very much like AI.
Tech backlash is alive & well in all fields.

I removed smart meter from my house after PG&E cut off electricity by mistake. Now they have to physically enter, and call me in advance to do so. So we need human oversight even there. Automatic AGI certification is a bit in the future.:)
Yeah, sounds a lot like my field, energy policy.
So it will end up as a techno-regulatory framework where judgment is legal and OSS-based and the laws demand the tech part is built in, unavoidable, current, certified.

I think international treaties (which may just agree on definitions & goals), research programs, and legal limits on acceptable applications of AI & AGI are needed. Totally agree that none of this can be enforced without OSS-based safety systems

We need provably beneficial AI, and here http:// humancompatible.ai will pave the way. We can then ensure that OSS engineers understand and adhere to HCAI metrics, and that those systems have them built-in. We need laws to ensure it's being done, certified, validated.

For example, should any govt use AI to make the decision to target an enemy or should that be solely left in human-decisionmaker (as part of rules of war)? Then we need good OSS safety systems to ensure that an AGI does not cross that decision boundary.

I agree that new laws will emerge and are needed. But the hard work still will be on the OSS front, or it will end up with a @PartnershipAI being basically MPAA, self-rating AI safe" and "PG-13", preempting govt oversight, Self-police with lobbyists before govt steps in? Nah."
A data set of vast variety of humans must be used to validate AI and AGI.

Are you’re saying regulating AI isn’t going to need new laws? Laws are written in words. I do agree that the testing & enforcement of laws may be through OSS & @OpenAI ’s safety systems will be very important for that. But there are some basic ideas govts need to agree upon.

Absolutely agreed. And the CoC, inclusion and self-improvement in OSS communities is unstoppable. We need to govern by elevating and refining the OSS community structures and processes. OSS developers promote underrepresented folks from within more and more, esp. in Bay Area.

Congress proved incapable of even basic understanding of Facebook economy, lest its AI. Words will only fend off oversight with lobbyist used to craft them. We need to self-govern via OSS process, elevating it to the level of policy. @fchollet shows the caliber of OSS leaders.

Also, regarding the original topic on diversity, IMO it is critical to keep AI-based discrimination on top of the AI regulatory agenda, despite some perceptions that is it a so-called ‘medium-term’ and not existential issue. How do we ensure an AGI doesn’t discriminate?

#AI is different from most other policy areas in that it is governed by software, most of it OSS, and we need to keep it that way, continuing what FSF started on a qualitatively new level. @OpenAI sets admirable example, due to @gdb and others. We should be able to run policy.

I submit that for #AI policy, open-source is key. Words are ambiguous while biases are complex. We need to hold all the corporate parents of @PartnershipAI accountable for releasing OSS versions of executable, verifiable policies. Otherwise it's a smokescreen just to feel good.

A lot of this (current law, gaps, new program/proposals) will be developed through Working Groups & discussion papers. Code is not the useful output for policy. But these are the critical pieces of information necessary.

What’s critical and missing from @OpenAI & @PartnershipAI ’s Congressional testimony is an understanding of what regulations currently govern AI & what gaps need to be filled with new law, regulatory authority for agencies, standards & test procedures, or AI professional norms.

Absolutely important. At the same time @PartnershipAI has better numbers and does seemingly nothing but spawning working groups editing reports. We need to push for @OpenAI to get better socially without becoming @PartnershipAI . Corporations have ethics levers; here, investors?

In 1980, even in 1997, it wasn't so obviously naive. But in 2017, I think it kinda is.
Obviously there are differences; I studied neuroscience myself. But assuming that algorithms can't be adapted to get the same ends is naive.
There are hundreds and hundreds of papers showing this in the evolutionary computation literature; I'm sure the NN literature has even more.
Fortunately, you can get exceptional mileage from just reoptimizing with the additional considerations explicitly coded and valued.
Expecting AIs to not evince bias on variables they have not been explicitly trained on is just naive.
In my own research, if you optimize for outcome X, then the optimizer ignores every other consideration than satisfy X.
I suspect that most of the X AI is racist/sexist/hetist/etc." biases can be largely fixed by explicitly reoptimizing to minimize bias."
